Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson received a call that there was an odor in the departure yard in Livonia. Manager Robinson responded and began searching for the odor. He found TILX 301778 had a small leak coming from the liquid valve where it is bolted to the pressure plate. Manager Robinson tightened the valve mounting bolts and the leak stopped. Manager Robinson called the shipper and told them to get an OTMA because the car leaked below the valve body.

XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a NA1993 Glycol Ether EB release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 cup of product released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor due to improper loading. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

CORROSIVE LIQUID was found being offloaded with a wet stain on the corner of package. Package was placed in a hazmat bin and brought to the hazardous waste cage and followed proper protocol.
Inner containers had loose caps which caused internal leakage. This package was brough to the hazmat cage for processing. Quality checks to ensure lids are properly sealed.

XPO-LOGISTICS contacted ERTS regarding five torn 55lb bags of Caustic Soda Beads. The reason for the incident is improper loading as the bags were torn by the trailer wall. This resulted in an estimated release of 250lbs of  product onto the wooden trailer floor in a 15’x4’ area. A Contractor was called to overpack the damaged bags,  cut-up the impacted tote, neutralize the trailer floor using a Vinegar Solution, and containerized the ripped  shrink wrap. One 55-gallon DF was generated for waste disposal. The remaining product was repalletized and  will ship on to the Consignee. No storm-drains, waterways or soil were impacted by this incident.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal NNW experienced a UN1824 Gardobond Additive H 7212 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 30-gallons of product released to a 15' x 15' area of the concrete dock floor, a 1' x 1' area of the concrete lot below the bay, and a 1' x 10' area of the trailer floor due to a puncture caused by the trailer wall. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. Absorbents and absorbent powder were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into a 95-gallon poly overpack. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column169: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a battery acid release from a 2113-pound battery. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of battery acid released to a 6’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and a 30’ x 2’ area of the concrete lot below due to improper loading; the battery fell over in transit. Absorbents and soda ash were worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. All impacted absorbents, pallet pieces, and debris were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The damaged battery was up righted and secured to a pallet. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On May 2, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1791 was damaged due to a manufacturing defect and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the loading dock, packaging, and adjacent items. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Patriot Environmental Services (PES) to remediate the impacted site. The crew overpacked the damaged drum in one (1) 95-gallon drum. PES deployed neutralizing agent and worked it in with rag. All impacted waste was containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column170: SHIPPERS NEED TO ENSURE ALL LIDS ARE TIGHT BEFORE SHIPPING PACKAGES.

column169: XPO-LOGISTICS contacted ERTS regarding a leaking lid on a 55-gallon poly drum containing SaniDate 5.0. The lid  appeared to be not sealed tight enough or not sealed correctly. This resulted in an estimated 1-cup release of product onto the top of the poly drum, the plastic shrink-wrap, and cardboard. A Contractor removed the  impacted plastic shrink wrap and cardboard and submerged them in water. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 95-gallon DF. In total, 2 drums of waste were generated for disposal. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil  were impacted by this incident.
